                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/310a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Consul at Los Mochis</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-29T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 29, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram in care of Collector of Customs at San
                    Diego.—Paraphrase.]</p>
                <p>Communication with the American Consul at Mazatlan is cut off and the Department
                    therefore desires you or commanding officer <hi rend="italic">Buford</hi> to
                    deliver to him the following telegram from the Department dated April 27, 1912:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The Department has informed the British Ambassador, in compliance with
                            request of British Government, that if there is room the <hi
                                rend="italic">Buford</hi> will be glad to extend assistance to any
                            British subjects who seek it after all Americans have been cared
                            for.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
